{
  "doc_id": "17075",
  "text": "As part of its post-translational metabolism, PrP C can undergo proteolytic cleavage events termed, in analogy to amyloid precursor protein processing, α-, β-, and possibly also γ-cleavage (Fig. 1) . These cleavage events release the so-called N1 + C1, N2 + C2, and C3 fragments, respectively [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] [CITATION_4] . These events may be important for both physiology and pathology. Alpha cleavage prevents the C1 fragment from being converted into PrP Sc [CITATION_5] , the rate of the beta cleavage is increased in the disease [CITATION_6] , and PrP C deletion mutants lacking the alpha-cleavage site show spontaneous neurodegeneration exhibiting pathological features distinct from those of prion diseases (reviewed in [CITATION_7] ).",
